<br>
I'm not gonna be a purist and for one second suggest that the game we play now is worse overall then the game we started playing.  No many things have been altered, are now nicer then they used to be.<br>
<br>
However...<br>
<br>
Our game has been gimped. It's now too easy. Yes, you can still die to massive unthinking trains. Yes, guard mobs in some zones are more powerful the entire *ZONES* in Kunark/Antonica and those the high end zones, too.<br>
<br>
This has had a detrious effect on the high end game most of all.  This is where a higher end guild takes these players and has to essentially break them of their bad habits to try and mold a player that will occasionally not screw up, versus one that can be depended on in all sorts of conditions.<br>
<br>
Some of us, like myself, recognize our limitations and play just one character. For every Listero, Tanilium or Cucullin, there are more and more people that achieve a lvl 60 character and then start over as another class in hopes of &quot;phat lewtz&quot; or &quot;groups&quot;.  There's very few fundamentelly solid ones.  There are very few Azzn's and Jarsek's, people capable of playing *any* class solidly, if not spectacularly in normal game play.<br>
<br>
Instead, the high end game finds itself littered with people applying that can't honestly tell you how many hp Vox or Nagafen had. Mostly because they had better items and couldn't be bothered to try and upgrade to any of the dragon items so the plvld past these encounters.<br>
<br>
Instead, they got up to lvl 53 then started putted points into AA for Run3 because everyone else did, and started the exp grind back up to 60.<br>
<br>
Totally missing out on the joys, rigors, and pains of many of the experiences that season a character. Exp grouping or soloing to 60, but never in a dangerous situation where they have to try and figure exactly how much mana they have, if that last nuke or heal is gonna save a raid.  Instead, they learn to chain cast heals/nukes, and are constantly surprised to find out that their instantly killed in large encounters because the basic fundamentals of how to integrate into a large body of people is missing.<br>
<br>
The ability to follow orders, to sacrifice some precious exp to save a logging out cleric...the ability to recognize that their class is more then just an offensive one or a defensive one. All missing.<br>
<br>
All missing because lvls &gt; all.<br>
<br>
There is no inherent right that lvls &gt; all and therefore phat lewtz.  The only advantage lvl 60 gives you is the ability to farm mobs in some zones better with less aggro. Yeah, I know, you'll resist AE's better, too...but the fact is....<br>
<br>
The fundamentals of the characters are still not solid.<br>
<br>
Should the game be more accessible to newer players? Yes. More accessible is good.  The newbie quests are *great* for this.<br>
<br>
But should it be *easier*.<br>
<br>
No.<br>
<br>
And unfortunately, it is. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/ukambok.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kambok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lenindara the Keeper </span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/26/02 6:01:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2764.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Gimpification of Norrath</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
